{"title_page": "Otto P\u00fcnter", "text_new": "{{Use British English| date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates| date=April 2020}}\n{{Under construction}}\n\n'''Otto P\u00fcnter''' (4 April 1900 - 13 October 1988)<ref name=HLS/> was a Swiss journalist who worked as an anti-Nazi [[resistance fighter]]. During the [[Second World War]], his codename was '''Pakbo''', and he was a member of the [[Red Orchestra (espionage)|Red Orchestra]].\n\n==Personal life==\nP\u00fcnter was born in [[Bern]], Switzerland.<ref name=HLS>{{cite web| url= https://hls-dhs-dss.ch/de/articles/041613/2009-10-27/| title= Otto P\u00fcnter| language=de| publisher=[[Historical Dictionary of Switzerland]]| date=27 October 2009| accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> His father was a merchant.<ref name=HLS/> He gained an [[apprenticeship]] from the [[University of Neuch\u00e2tel]].<ref name=ETHZ>{{cite web| url= http://onlinearchives.ethz.ch/ReportViewer.aspx?obj=9a11cd27ba5c4ea2ab852953e5676170&format=PDF| format=PDF| title=Nachl\u00e4sse und Einzelbest\u00e4nde / N-R / P\u00fcnter, Otto| language=de| publisher=[[ETH Zurich]]| accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1927, P\u00fcnter began working for \"Res Publica\".<ref name=ETHZ/> During the [[Spanish Civil War]], post-war studies into espionage groups claim that P\u00fcnter had built his own intelligence network, in order to sell secrets to the French and British.<ref name=Day>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IvLXCQAAQBAJ| title= The Bedbug: Klop Ustinov: Britain's Most Ingenious Spy| last=Day| first=Peter| publisher=[[Biteback Publishing]]| date=2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], P\u00fcnter was a member of the [[Red Orchestra (espionage)|Red Orchestra]].<ref name=HLS/> His codename was Pakbo,<ref name=HLS/> and P\u00fcnter worked with the Soviet intelligence agencies.<ref name=HLS/> Others in the movement included [[Georges Blun]] and [[Rachel D\u00fcbendorfer]],<ref>{{cite book| url= https://www.worldcat.org/wcpa/servlet/DCARead?standardNo=0891417109&standardNoType=1&excerpt=true| title= Hitler's Traitor: Martin Bormann and the Defeat of the Reich | last=Kilzer| first=Louis| publisher=[[Presidio Press]]|via=[[WorldCat]]| date=2000|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=HohPaIyc5G0C&dq=Rachel+D%C3%BCbendorfer&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title= A Century of Spies: Intelligence in the Twentieth Century| last=Richelson| first=Jeffrey T.| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]| page=127| date=1997| access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> and they collaborated with Hungarian spy [[Alexander Rad\u00f3]].<ref name=ACI>{{cite web|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080820133515/http://www.acipss.org/intelligence/beitraege/die_schweiz_im_2wk/geheimdienste_und_widerstand.htm|\ntitle=Die Schweiz im Zweiten Weltkrieg| language=de|publisher=Austrian Center for Intelligence, Propaganda & Security Studies| date=20 Aug 2008| accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=smHzCwAAQBAJ| title=Resistance: European Resistance to the Nazis, 1940-1945| last=Foot| first=M. R. D. | publisher=[[Biteback Publishing]]| date=2016}}</ref> Rad\u00f3 was accused of using P\u00fcnter to sell information to the British secret service.<ref name=Day/>\n\nAfter the War, he became President of the Association of Federal Parliament Journalists.<ref name=HLS/> From 1656 to 1965, he was the head of the [[Swiss Broadcasting Corporation]] (SRG).<ref name=HLS/><ref name=ETHZ/> In 1966, he appeared on a panel discussion show about Switzerland's involvement in the Second World War.<ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=11l9BuA7gOIC| title=Secret Channel to Berlin: The Masson-Schellenberg Connection and Swiss Intelligence in World War II| last=Braunschweig| first=Pierre| publisher=[[Casemate Publishers]]| date=2004| pages=272, 496}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1975, he was awarded the [[Hans Bredow]] medal for services to radio. The ceremony was in [[West Berlin]].<ref name=HLS/><ref name=ETHZ/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English| date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates| date=April 2020}}\n{{Under construction}}\n\n'''Otto P\u00fcnter''' (4 April 1900 - 13 October 1988)<ref name=HLS/> was a Swiss journalist who worked as an anti-Nazi [[resistance fighter]]. During the [[Second World War]], his codename was '''Pakbo''', and he was a member of the [[Red Orchestra (espionage)|Red Orchestra]].\n\n==Personal life==\nP\u00fcnter was born in [[Bern]], Switzerland.<ref name=HLS>{{cite web| url= https://hls-dhs-dss.ch/de/articles/041613/2009-10-27/| title= Otto P\u00fcnter| language=de| publisher=[[Historical Dictionary of Switzerland]]| date=27 October 2009| accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> His father was a merchant.<ref name=HLS/> He gained an [[apprenticeship]] from the [[University of Neuch\u00e2tel]].<ref name=ETHZ>{{cite web| url= http://onlinearchives.ethz.ch/ReportViewer.aspx?obj=9a11cd27ba5c4ea2ab852953e5676170&format=PDF| format=PDF| title=Nachl\u00e4sse und Einzelbest\u00e4nde / N-R / P\u00fcnter, Otto| language=de| publisher=[[ETH Zurich]]| accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1927, P\u00fcnter began working for \"Res Publica\".<ref name=ETHZ/> During the [[Spanish Civil War]], post-war studies into espionage groups claim that P\u00fcnter had built his own intelligence network, in order to sell secrets to the French and British.<ref name=Day>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IvLXCQAAQBAJ| title= The Bedbug: Klop Ustinov: Britain's Most Ingenious Spy| last=Day| first=Peter| publisher=[[Biteback Publishing]]| date=2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], P\u00fcnter was a member of the [[Red Orchestra (espionage)|Red Orchestra]].<ref name=HLS/> His codename was Pakbo,<ref name=HLS/> and P\u00fcnter worked with the Soviet intelligence agencies.<ref name=HLS/> Others in the movement included [[Georges Blun]] and [[Rachel D\u00fcbendorfer]],<ref>{{cite book| url= https://www.worldcat.org/wcpa/servlet/DCARead?standardNo=0891417109&standardNoType=1&excerpt=true| title= Hitler's Traitor: Martin Bormann and the Defeat of the Reich | last=Kilzer| first=Louis| publisher=[[Presidio Press]]|via=[[WorldCat]]| date=2000|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=HohPaIyc5G0C&dq=Rachel+D%C3%BCbendorfer&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title= A Century of Spies: Intelligence in the Twentieth Century| last=Richelson| first=Jeffrey T.| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]| page=127| date=1997| access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> and they collaborated with Hungarian spy [[Alexander Rad\u00f3]].<ref name=ACI>{{cite web|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080820133515/http://www.acipss.org/intelligence/beitraege/die_schweiz_im_2wk/geheimdienste_und_widerstand.htm|\ntitle=Die Schweiz im Zweiten Weltkrieg| language=de|publisher=Austrian Center for Intelligence, Propaganda & Security Studies| date=20 Aug 2008| accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=smHzCwAAQBAJ| title=Resistance: European Resistance to the Nazis, 1940-1945| last=Foot| first=M. R. D. | publisher=[[Biteback Publishing]]| date=2016}}</ref> Rad\u00f3 was accused of using P\u00fcnter to sell information to the British secret service.<ref name=Day/>\n\nAfter the War, he became President of the Association of Federal Parliament Journalists.<ref name=HLS/> From 1656 to 1965, he was the head of the [[Swiss Broadcasting Corporation]] (SRG).<ref name=HLS/><ref name=ETHZ/> In 1966, he appeared on a panel discussion show about Switzerland's involvement in the Second World War.<ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=11l9BuA7gOIC| title=Secret Channel to Berlin: The Masson-Schellenberg Connection and Swiss Intelligence in World War II| last=Braunschweig| first=Pierre| publisher=[[Casemate Publishers]]| date=2004| pages=272, 496\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1975, he was awarded the [[Hans Bredow]] medal for services to radio. The ceremony was in [[West Berlin]].<ref name=HLS/><ref name=ETHZ/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Joseph2302", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:ref fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Otto_P%C3%BCnter"}
{"title_page": "Oros\u00ed Volcano", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Oros\u00ed Volcano\n| photo = Oros\u00ed.jpg\n| photo_caption = SW view of Orosi, 1989\n| elevation_m = 1659\n| elevation_ref = <ref name=gvp>{{cite gvp|vnum=1405-01=|name=Oros\u00ed|accessdate=2010-03-11}}</ref>\n| prominence = \n| prominence_ref = \n| map = Costa Rica\n| label_position = right\n| listing = [[List of volcanoes in Costa Rica]]\n| location = [[Costa Rica]]\n| range = [[Cordillera de Guanacaste]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|10|58|48|N|85|28|24|W|type:mountain_region:CR_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=gvp/>\n| topo = \n| type = [[Stratovolcano]]\n| age = \n| last_eruption = ~3500 years ago<ref name=gvp/>\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\nThe '''Oros\u00ed Volcano''', in Spanish the {{lang|es|'''Volc\u00e1n Oros\u00ed'''}}, is an [[inactive volcano]] in [[Costa Rica]], situated in the [[Cordillera de Guanacaste]] near the border with [[Nicaragua]]. The area around the volcano is a popular tourist destination, especially for more ecologically minded tourists due to its biodiversity, including the [[Guanacaste National Park (Costa Rica)|Guanacaste National Park]].\n\n''Volc\u00e1n Oros\u00ed'' itself has a conical shape as viewed from the north or west, but its flanks are heavily eroded. The complex includes Oros\u00ed, Orosilito, Volc\u00e1n Pedregal, and Cacao. The highest peak of the volcanic complex is 1659-m-high Volc\u00e1n Cacao, 5.5 km SE of Oros\u00ed.  Historical eruptions were reported from Oros\u00ed in 1844 and 1849, but even at the time of the first volcanological observations at the end of the 19th century, Oros\u00ed was overgrown with large trees, and the eruptions may actually have been from neighboring [[Rinc\u00f3n de la Vieja Volcano|Rinc\u00f3n de la Vieja]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=345010|title=Global Volcanism Program {{!}} Oros\u00ed|website=volcano.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\nAt the base of the volcano is the [[Maritza Biological Station]], which researches aquatic biology, founded in conjunction with [[Stroud Water Research Center]], Avondale, Pennsylvania, USA.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Mountains of Costa Rica}}\n{{Volcanoes of Costa Rica}}\n{{Central American volcanoes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orosi Volcano}}\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Inactive volcanoes]]\n\n\n{{CostaRica-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Oros\u00ed Volcano\n| photo = Oros\u00ed.jpg\n| photo_caption = SW view of Orosi, 1989\n| elevation_m = 1659\n| elevation_ref = <ref name=gvp>{{cite gvp|vnum=1405-01=|name=Oros\u00ed|accessdate=2010-03-11}}</ref>\n| prominence = \n| prominence_ref = \n| map = Costa Rica\n| label_position = right\n| listing = [[List of volcanoes in Costa Rica]]\n| location = [[Costa Rica]]\n| range = [[Cordillera de Guanacaste]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|10|58|48|N|85|28|24|W|type:mountain_region:CR_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=gvp/>\n| topo = \n| type = [[Stratovolcano]]\n| age = \n| last_eruption = ~3500 years ago<ref name=gvp/>\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\nThe '''Oros\u00ed Volcano''', in Spanish the {{lang|es|'''Volc\u00e1n Oros\u00ed'''}}, is an [[inactive volcano]] in [[Costa Rica]], situated in the [[Cordillera de Guanacaste]] near the border with [[Nicaragua]]. The area around the volcano is a popular tourist destination, especially for more ecologically minded tourists due to its biodiversity, including the [[Guanacaste National Park (Costa Rica)|Guanacaste National Park]].\n\n''Volc\u00e1n Oros\u00ed'' itself has a conical shape as viewed from the north or west, but its flanks are heavily eroded. The complex includes Oros\u00ed, Orosilito, Volc\u00e1n Pedregal, and Cacao. The highest peak of the volcanic complex is 1659-m-high Volc\u00e1n Cacao, 5.5 km SE of Oros\u00ed.  Historical eruptions were reported from Oros\u00ed in 1844 and 1849, but even at the time of the first volcanological observations at the end of the 19th century, Oros\u00ed was overgrown with large trees, and the eruptions may actually have been from neighboring [[Rinc\u00f3n de la Vieja Volcano|Rinc\u00f3n de la Vieja]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=345010|title=Global Volcanism Program {{!}} Oros\u00ed|website=volcano.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\nAt the base of the volcano is the [[Maritza Biological Station]], which researches aquatic biology, founded in conjunction with [[Stroud Water Research Center]], Avondale, Pennsylvania, USA.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Mountains of Costa Rica}}\n{{Central American volcanoes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orosi Volcano}}\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Inactive volcanoes]]\n\n\n{{CostaRica-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Roqz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oros%C3%AD_Volcano"}
{"title_page": "Matt Reeves", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Matt Reeves\n| image = Matt Reeves (13948765595) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Reeves in 2014\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Mindarie, Perth]]\n| home_town = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Southern California]]\n| occupation = {{hlist|Reevsy|Kinder-garden Teacher|Child Home=Video Producer}}\n| yearsactive = 1994\u2013present\n| spouse = Melinda Wang\n| children = 1\n| website = \n}}\n'''Matt Reeves''' is an American filmmaker. After several years working in film and television, Reeves made his cinematic directorial debut with ''[[The Pallbearer]]'' (1996). He came to widespread attention with the mainstream hit ''[[Cloverfield]]'' (2008), going on to helm the romantic horror film remake ''[[Let Me In (film)|Let Me In]]'' (2010) and the critically acclaimed science fiction sequels ''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]'' (2014) and ''[[War for the Planet of the Apes]]'' (2017). \n\nReeves will direct, write and produce the upcoming superhero film ''[[The Batman (film)|The Batman]]'' (2021), which is set in the [[DC Comics|DC Universe]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Rockville Centre, New York]], Reeves' family moved to Los Angeles when he was five, where he began making movies at age eight, directing friends and using a wind-up camera.<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/director-matt-reeves-on-dawn-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-1404417101 |url-access=subscription |title=Director Matt Reeves on 'Dawn of the Planet of the Apes' |first=Alexandra |last=Wolfe |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=July 3, 2014 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Reeves met and befriended filmmaker [[J.J. Abrams]] when both were 13 years old<ref name=\"vanityfair\">[[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]] in {{cite news |title=What Star Wars: The Force Awakens Producer Kathleen Kennedy Learned From Working With a Teenage J.J. Abrams |first=Bruce |last=Handy |date=May 20, 2015 |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/05/kathleen-kennedy-star-wars-interview |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> and a Los Angeles [[public-access television]] cable channel, [[Z Channel]],<ref>Neil Daniels {{google books|TnsuCgAAQBAJ|JJ Abrams - A Study in Genius: The Unofficial Biography|page=54}}</ref> was airing their short films. When Reeves and Abrams were 15 or 16 years old, [[Steven Spielberg]] hired them to transfer some of his own [[Super 8 film]]s to videotape.<ref name=\"vanityfair\"/>\n\nReeves attended the [[University of Southern California]]. There, between 1991 and 1992, he produced an award-winning student film, ''Mr. Petrified Forest'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Campbell|first1=Christopher|title=Watch \u2018Mr. Petrified Forrest,\u2019 the Debut Film By \u2018Dawn of the Planet of the Apes\u2019 Helmer Matt Reeves|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/watch-mr-petrified-forrest-the-debut-film-by-dawn-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-helmer-matt-reeves-8ae55e349d11#.bqamfeohu|date=7 July 2014|publisher=filmschoolrejects.com|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> which helped him acquire an agent; he also co-wrote a script that eventually became ''[[Under Siege 2: Dark Territory]]''. After graduating, he co-wrote ''[[Cloverfield]]'' which became his professional directorial debut.\n\n==Career==\nReeves and Abrams co-created the TV series ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'',<ref>David Hofstede {{google books|0bCxW4fs_BwC|5000 Episodes and No Commercials: The Ultimate Guide to TV Shows On DVD|page=221}}</ref> for which Reeves directed several episodes, including the pilot. Reeves has helmed occasional episodes of other television series, including ''[[Relativity (TV series)|Relativity]]'' and ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]'', among others.\n\nReeves directed the 2008 monster science fiction film ''[[Cloverfield]]'', which Abrams produced;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18534 |title=00's Retrospect: Horror Softens Up in 2008 |publisher=Bloody-disgusting.com |date= |accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref> Reeves later served as an executive producer on ''[[10 Cloverfield Lane]]'' and ''[[The Cloverfield Paradox]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36395/matt-reeves-talks-cloverfield-2 |title=Matt Reeves Talks Cloverfield 2 |publisher=[[Dreadcentral.com]] |date=March 13, 2010 |accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref> Reeves wrote and directed ''[[Let Me In (film)|Let Me In]]'', a remake of the [[Swedish cinema|Swedish film]] ''[[Let the Right One In (film)|Let the Right One In]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35427/matt-reeves-talks-let-me-in-promises-a-darker-experience |title=Matt Reeves Talks DayCation \u2013 Promises a Darker Experience |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date= |accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref> which was released on October 1, 2010, by Overture Films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18770 |title='DayCation' Dark and More Thrilling Than 'Twilight' |publisher=Bloody-disgusting.com |date= |accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, Reeves signed on to direct a film based on the classic television series ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming Jr.|first=Mike|url=https://deadline.com/2011/10/exclusive-matt-reeves-is-warner-bros-pick-for-twilight-zone-movie-183410/|title=Exclusive! Matt Reeves Is Warner Bros' Pick For 'Twilight Zone' Movie|date=October 15, 2011|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> but he left the project in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|url=https://collider.com/matt-reeves-not-directing-twilight-zone/|title=Matt Reeves No Longer Directing The Twilight Zone|date=September 25, 2012|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]}}</ref> Reeves directed the science fiction film ''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]'', the sequel to ''[[Rise of the Planet of the Apes]]'', released in 2014. He returned to direct and write the third film in the series, ''[[War for the Planet of the Apes]]'', which was released on July 14, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3327031/sorry-ya-damned-dirty-apes-next-sequel-moved-2017/|title=Sorry, Ya' Damned Dirty 'Apes,' Next Sequel Moved to 2017 - Bloody Disgusting!|date=January 6, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Upcoming projects===\nIn February 2017, Reeves was hired to direct and produce a [[Batman]] film, titled ''[[The Batman (film)|The Batman]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Couch|first=Aaron|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/batman-matt-reeves-closes-deal-direct-produce-979082|title='The Batman': Matt Reeves Closes Deal to Direct and Produce|date=February 23, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=McMillan|first=Graeme|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/batman-director-clarifies-yes-batman-exists-dc-extended-universe-1032390|title=Yes, 'The Batman' Exists in the DC Extended Universe, Director Says|date=August 24, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> He co-wrote the screenplay with [[Mattson Tomlin]], and principal photography commenced in January 2020.<ref name=\"TheBatmanFilmingBegin\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/the-batman-finds-its-selina-kyle-in-zoe-kravitz-1202759926/ |title='The Batman' Finds Its Selina Kyle In Zo\u00eb Kravitz |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=October 14, 2019 |access-date=October 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014210307/https://deadline.com/2019/10/the-batman-finds-its-selina-kyle-in-zoe-kravitz-1202759926/ |archive-date=October 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Pearson|first=Ben|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-batman-has-begun-filming/|title=Criminals of Gotham, Beware: 'The Batman' Has Begun Filming|date=January 6, 2020|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[/Film]]}}</ref> ''The Batman'' is scheduled to be released on June 25, 2021, and will star [[Robert Pattinson]].<ref name=\"TheBatmanFilmingBegin\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nReeves is married to Melinda Wang, a former animator. They have one son together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/director-matt-reeves-on-dawn-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-1404417101|title=Director Matt Reeves on 'Dawn of the Planet of the Apes'|first=Alexandra|last=Wolfe|date=July 3, 2014|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url-access=registration|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! colspan=\"3\" |Credited as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n! width=65 | [[Film director|Director]]\n! width=65 | [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=65 | [[Film producer|Producer]]\n|-\n|1993\n|''Future Shock''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Segment: \"Mr. Petrified Forest\"\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Under Siege 2: Dark Territory]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Co-written with [[Richard Hatem]]\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[The Pallbearer]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Co-written with [[Jason Katims]]\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Yards]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Co-written with [[James Gray (director)|James Gray]]\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Cloverfield]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Let Me In (film)|Let Me In]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[War for the Planet of the Apes]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Co-written with [[Mark Bomback]]\n|-\n|2021\n|''[[The Batman (film)|The Batman]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|Co-written with [[Mattson Tomlin]]; Filming\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Executive producer'''\n* ''[[10 Cloverfield Lane]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[The Cloverfield Paradox]]'' (2018)\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n! colspan=\"3\"|Credited as\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Notes\n|-\n! width=65 | [[Television director|Director]]\n! width=65 | [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=65 | [[Television producer|Executive<br>producer]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1997\n| ''[[Relativity (TV series)|Relativity]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n| Episode \"Billable Hours\"\n|-\n| ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n| Episode \"All is Bright\"\n|-\n| 1998\u20132002\n| ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'' \n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n| Co-creator and showrunner with [[J. J. Abrams]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Gideon's Crossing]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n| Episode \"The Gift\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2006\n| ''[[Miracles (TV series)|Miracles]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n| Episode \"The Ferguson Syndrome\"\n|-\n| ''[[Conviction (2006 TV series)|Conviction]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n| Episode \"Pilot\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2019\n| ''[[The Passage (TV series)|The Passage]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| ''Surveillance''\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes}}\n|Unsold TV pilot\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Tales from the Loop]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes}}\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nCritical, public and commercial reception to films Reeves has directed as of July 20, 2018.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Film\n! [[Rotten Tomatoes]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Matt Reeves | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/162676600/ | website=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref>\n! [[Metacritic]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Matt Reeves |url=http://www.metacritic.com/person/matt-reeves | website=Metacritic |accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref>\n! [[CinemaScore]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cinemascore.com/ | title=CinemaScore | work=cinemascore.com | accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref>\n! Budget\n! Box office<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Director&id=mattreeves.htm | title=Matt Reeves Movie Box office | publisher=[[Amazon.com]] | work=boxofficemojo.com | accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Pallbearer]]'' || 45% (20 reviews)<ref>[[Rotten Tomatoes]], \"[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pallbearer/ The Pallbearer (1996)]\". Accessed December 25, 2014.</ref> || {{N/A}} || {{N/A}} || $5 million || $7.65 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pallbearer.htm|title=The Pallbearer (1996) - Box Office Mojo|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=2010-02-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Cloverfield]]'' || 77% (204 reviews) || 64 (37 reviews) || C || $25 million || $170.8 million\n|-\n| ''[[Let Me In (film)|Let Me In]]'' || 88% (226 reviews) || 79 (35 reviews) || C+ || $20 million || $24.1 million\n|-\n| ''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]'' || 91% (306 reviews) || 79 (48 reviews) || A\u2013 || $170 million || $710.6 million\n|-\n| ''[[War for the Planet of the Apes]]'' || 94% (343 reviews) || 82 (50 reviews) || A\u2013 || $150 million || $490.7 million\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111001210105/http://laist.com/2008/01/09/laist_interview_88.php LAist.com Interview with Matt Reeves]\n{{Matt Reeves}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reeves, Matt}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American soap opera writers]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Science fiction film directors]]\n[[Category:Horror film directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Rockville Centre, New York]]\n[[Category:USC School of Cinematic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Matt Reeves\n| image = Matt Reeves (13948765595) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Reeves in 2014\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Rockville Centre, New York]]\n| home_town = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Southern California]]\n| occupation = {{hlist|Film director|screenwriter|producer}}\n| yearsactive = 1994\u2013present\n| spouse = Melinda Wang\n| children = 1\n| website = \n}}\n'''Matt Reeves''' is an American filmmaker. After several years working in film and television, Reeves made his cinematic directorial debut with ''[[The Pallbearer]]'' (1996). He came to widespread attention with the mainstream hit ''[[Cloverfield]]'' (2008), going on to helm the romantic horror film remake ''[[Let Me In (film)|Let Me In]]'' (2010) and the critically acclaimed science fiction sequels ''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]'' (2014) and ''[[War for the Planet of the Apes]]'' (2017). \n\nReeves will direct, write and produce the upcoming superhero film ''[[The Batman (film)|The Batman]]'' (2021), which is set in the [[DC Comics|DC Universe]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Rockville Centre, New York]], Reeves' family moved to Los Angeles when he was five, where he began making movies at age eight, directing friends and using a wind-up camera.<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/director-matt-reeves-on-dawn-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-1404417101 |url-access=subscription |title=Director Matt Reeves on 'Dawn of the Planet of the Apes' |first=Alexandra |last=Wolfe |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=July 3, 2014 |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Reeves met and befriended filmmaker [[J.J. Abrams]] when both were 13 years old<ref name=\"vanityfair\">[[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]] in {{cite news |title=What Star Wars: The Force Awakens Producer Kathleen Kennedy Learned From Working With a Teenage J.J. Abrams |first=Bruce |last=Handy |date=May 20, 2015 |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/05/kathleen-kennedy-star-wars-interview |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> and a Los Angeles [[public-access television]] cable channel, [[Z Channel]],<ref>Neil Daniels {{google books|TnsuCgAAQBAJ|JJ Abrams - A Study in Genius: The Unofficial Biography|page=54}}</ref> was airing their short films. When Reeves and Abrams were 15 or 16 years old, [[Steven Spielberg]] hired them to transfer some of his own [[Super 8 film]]s to videotape.<ref name=\"vanityfair\"/>\n\nReeves attended the [[University of Southern California]]. There, between 1991 and 1992, he produced an award-winning student film, ''Mr. Petrified Forest'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Campbell|first1=Christopher|title=Watch \u2018Mr. Petrified Forrest,\u2019 the Debut Film By \u2018Dawn of the Planet of the Apes\u2019 Helmer Matt Reeves|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/watch-mr-petrified-forrest-the-debut-film-by-dawn-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-helmer-matt-reeves-8ae55e349d11#.bqamfeohu|date=7 July 2014|publisher=filmschoolrejects.com|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> which helped him acquire an agent; he also co-wrote a script that eventually became ''[[Under Siege 2: Dark Territory]]''. After graduating, he co-wrote ''[[Cloverfield]]'' which became his professional directorial debut.\n\n==Career==\nReeves and Abrams co-created the TV series ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'',<ref>David Hofstede {{google books|0bCxW4fs_BwC|5000 Episodes and No Commercials: The Ultimate Guide to TV Shows On DVD|page=221}}</ref> for which Reeves directed several episodes, including the pilot. Reeves has helmed occasional episodes of other television series, including ''[[Relativity (TV series)|Relativity]]'' and ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]'', among others.\n\nReeves directed the 2008 monster science fiction film ''[[Cloverfield]]'', which Abrams produced;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18534 |title=00's Retrospect: Horror Softens Up in 2008 |publisher=Bloody-disgusting.com |date= |accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref> Reeves later served as an executive producer on ''[[10 Cloverfield Lane]]'' and ''[[The Cloverfield Paradox]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36395/matt-reeves-talks-cloverfield-2 |title=Matt Reeves Talks Cloverfield 2 |publisher=[[Dreadcentral.com]] |date=March 13, 2010 |accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref> Reeves wrote and directed ''[[Let Me In (film)|Let Me In]]'', a remake of the [[Swedish cinema|Swedish film]] ''[[Let the Right One In (film)|Let the Right One In]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35427/matt-reeves-talks-let-me-in-promises-a-darker-experience |title=Matt Reeves Talks DayCation \u2013 Promises a Darker Experience |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date= |accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref> which was released on October 1, 2010, by Overture Films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18770 |title='DayCation' Dark and More Thrilling Than 'Twilight' |publisher=Bloody-disgusting.com |date= |accessdate=October 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, Reeves signed on to direct a film based on the classic television series ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming Jr.|first=Mike|url=https://deadline.com/2011/10/exclusive-matt-reeves-is-warner-bros-pick-for-twilight-zone-movie-183410/|title=Exclusive! Matt Reeves Is Warner Bros' Pick For 'Twilight Zone' Movie|date=October 15, 2011|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> but he left the project in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|url=https://collider.com/matt-reeves-not-directing-twilight-zone/|title=Matt Reeves No Longer Directing The Twilight Zone|date=September 25, 2012|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]}}</ref> Reeves directed the science fiction film ''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]'', the sequel to ''[[Rise of the Planet of the Apes]]'', released in 2014. He returned to direct and write the third film in the series, ''[[War for the Planet of the Apes]]'', which was released on July 14, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3327031/sorry-ya-damned-dirty-apes-next-sequel-moved-2017/|title=Sorry, Ya' Damned Dirty 'Apes,' Next Sequel Moved to 2017 - Bloody Disgusting!|date=January 6, 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Upcoming projects===\nIn February 2017, Reeves was hired to direct and produce a [[Batman]] film, titled ''[[The Batman (film)|The Batman]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Couch|first=Aaron|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/batman-matt-reeves-closes-deal-direct-produce-979082|title='The Batman': Matt Reeves Closes Deal to Direct and Produce|date=February 23, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=McMillan|first=Graeme|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/batman-director-clarifies-yes-batman-exists-dc-extended-universe-1032390|title=Yes, 'The Batman' Exists in the DC Extended Universe, Director Says|date=August 24, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> He co-wrote the screenplay with [[Mattson Tomlin]], and principal photography commenced in January 2020.<ref name=\"TheBatmanFilmingBegin\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/the-batman-finds-its-selina-kyle-in-zoe-kravitz-1202759926/ |title='The Batman' Finds Its Selina Kyle In Zo\u00eb Kravitz |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=October 14, 2019 |access-date=October 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014210307/https://deadline.com/2019/10/the-batman-finds-its-selina-kyle-in-zoe-kravitz-1202759926/ |archive-date=October 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Pearson|first=Ben|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-batman-has-begun-filming/|title=Criminals of Gotham, Beware: 'The Batman' Has Begun Filming|date=January 6, 2020|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[/Film]]}}</ref> ''The Batman'' is scheduled to be released on June 25, 2021, and will star [[Robert Pattinson]].<ref name=\"TheBatmanFilmingBegin\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nReeves is married to Melinda Wang, a former animator. They have one son together.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/director-matt-reeves-on-dawn-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-1404417101|title=Director Matt Reeves on 'Dawn of the Planet of the Apes'|first=Alexandra|last=Wolfe|date=July 3, 2014|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url-access=registration|accessdate=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! colspan=\"3\" |Credited as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n! width=65 | [[Film director|Director]]\n! width=65 | [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=65 | [[Film producer|Producer]]\n|-\n|1993\n|''Future Shock''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Segment: \"Mr. Petrified Forest\"\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Under Siege 2: Dark Territory]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Co-written with [[Richard Hatem]]\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[The Pallbearer]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Co-written with [[Jason Katims]]\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Yards]]''\n|{{no}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Co-written with [[James Gray (director)|James Gray]]\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Cloverfield]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Let Me In (film)|Let Me In]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[War for the Planet of the Apes]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}}\n|Co-written with [[Mark Bomback]]\n|-\n|2021\n|''[[The Batman (film)|The Batman]]''\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|Co-written with [[Mattson Tomlin]]; Filming\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Executive producer'''\