b|url=https://www.prowrestling.com/wwe-reschedules-upcoming-south-africa-tour-due-to-coronavirus/|title=WWE Reschedules Upcoming South Africa Tour Due To Coronavirus|date=2020-03-20|website=ProWrestling.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n'''Religious'''\n*[[Zion Christian Church]] (ZCC) Easter pilgrimage, cancelled until further notice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/trips-to-moria-on-hold-until-further-notice-over-coronavirus-pandemic-zcc-tells-congregants-20200317|title=Trips to Moria on hold until further notice over coronavirus pandemic, ZCC tells congregants|website=news24.com|date=17 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*[[Muslim Judicial Council]] (MJC) suspends [[Friday prayer]]<nowiki/>s but keeps mosques open. As of Sunday, 22 March, mosques have closed but the call to prayer will still be given.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/coronavirus-mjc-suspends-jumuah-prayers-but-no-call-to-close-mosques-20200318|title=Coronavirus: MJC suspends Jumuah prayers, but no call to close mosques|date=2020-03-18|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*Chief Rabbi [[Warren Goldstein]] suspends Synagogues.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Africa's shuls close to stop spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.sajr.co.za/news-and-articles/2020/03/19/south-africa-s-shuls-close-to-stop-spread-of-coronavirus |work=South Africa Jewish Report |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Traditional circumcision schools in Eastern Cape suspended.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sizani |first1=Mkhuseli |title=Coronavirus: Traditional circumcision schools in Eastern Cape suspended |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/coronavirus-traditional-circumcision-schools-in-eastern-cape-suspended-20200323 |accessdate=|website=News24}}</ref>\n\n'''Expo & Trade shows'''\n*HuntEx, postponed until unknown future date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huntex.net/|title=HuntEx2020 {{!}} Ten Years Inspiring Adventure|website=www.huntex.net|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*DecorEx Cape Town & Durban, postponed until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://decorex.co.za/|title=HOME|website=Decorex Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*Tyrexpo, postponed to 4\u20136 August 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tyrexpoafrica.com/attention.php|title=Tyrexpo Africa 2020|website=www.tyrexpoafrica.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*Power & Electricity World expo, postponed until 20\u201321 August 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.terrapinn.com/exhibition/power-electricity-world-africa/Event-Postponement.stm|title=Event Postponement {{!}} Power & Electricity|date=2020-03-23|website=Power & Electricity World Africa 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n'''Other'''\n*[[University of Pretoria]], [[University of Cape Town]], [[Stellenbosch University]], [[Rhodes University]], [[University of KwaZulu Natal]] and [[Durban University of Technology]] graduation ceremonies cancelled or postponed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/03/13/stellenbosch-uct-cancel-upcoming-graduations-due-to-coronavirus|title=STELLENBOSCH, UCT CANCEL UPCOMING GRADUATIONS DUE TO CORONAVIRUS|last1=Kassen|first1=Jarita|website=EWN|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/coronavirus-in-sa-uct-graduations-suspended-amid-covid-19-concerns-20200314|title=Coronavirus in SA: UCT graduations suspended amid Covid-19 concerns|last1=McCain|first1=Nicole|website=News24|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-03-16-universities-cancelling-in-person-classes-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Universities cancelling in-person classes due to coronavirus|website=SowetanLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.up.ac.za/news/post_2881150-update-postponement-of-contact-classes-and-rescheduling-of-academic-calendar- |title = UPDATE: Postponement of contact classes and rescheduling of academic calendar}}</ref>\n*[[List of comic book conventions|Comic Con]] Cape Town, postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/whats-on/cape-town/comic-con-cape-town-postponed-to-2021-45138721|title=Comic Con Cape Town postponed to 2021|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*Agricultural events such as the [[Pietermaritzburg]] Royal Show, SA Cheese Festival, Qualit\u00e9 Awards Dinner, and Agri-Expo Western Cape Youth Show, cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodformzansi.co.za/covid-19-farmers-urged-to-protect-themselves-workers/|title=COVID-19: Farmers urged to protect themselves, workers|last=Ngcakani|first=Noluthando|date=2020-03-16|website=Food For Mzansi|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] [[Lifesaving South Africa]], national championships cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/wimpy-lifesaving-south-africa-national-championships-cancelled-44956403|title=Wimpy Lifesaving South Africa National Championships cancelled|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Scouts South Africa]], all Scouting activity suspended until schools reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scouts.org.za/2020/03/16/scouting-suspended-in-response-to-covid-19/|title=Scouting suspended in response to COVID-19|website=www.scouts.org.za|date=16 March 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[Johannesburg|City of Johannesburg]], all public facilities closed indefinitely including public swimming pools, recreational and civic centres, stadiums, libraries, sporting facilities, and the [[Johannesburg Zoo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2257497/city-of-joburg-closes-all-public-facilities-including-pools-theatres-and-the-zoo/|title=City of Joburg closes all public facilities, including pools, theatres and the zoo |agency=News24 Wire |website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[EThekwini Metropolitan Municipality|Ethekhwini Metropolitan Municipality]] closed all of [[Durban]]'s public facilities including swimming pools, beaches, libraries, community halls, and museums while restrictions have been put in place for the [[Durban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than {{val|7500}} MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer \u2013 here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|accessdate=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation ==\n{{Main|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe spreading of [[fake news]] and other misinformation in South Africa about the virus is an offence punishable with either a fine, six months' imprisonment, or both.<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" />\n\nThe arrival of the COVID-19 virus in South Africa saw an increase in the dissemination of misinformation about the virus on social media and other platforms. These range from messages minimising the virus's harm in the country<ref name=\"MaverickFake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-31-viral-outbreak-fake-news-spreads-in-sa-in-tandem-with-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus Fact Check#1: Viral outbreak: Fake news spreads in SA in tandem with Covid-19|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> to the propagation of [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] about government actions to control the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fake-news-no-covid-19-testing-kits-are-not-contaminated-20200406|title=FAKE NEWS: No, Covid-19 testing kits are not contaminated|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=News24|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>   \n\nOne individual was arrested for posting a video showing himself drinking in public with friends following the national lockdown whilst stating that there was \"nothing called corona here\".<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" /> In another incident a man claimed that 10,000 government officials would be going door-to-door using contaminated test kits to test people for the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\" /> A conspiracy theory that [[Bill Gates]] wished to test a COVID-19 \"vaccine\" in Africa or South Africa first caused significant controversy on social media<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-06-bill-gates-trevor-noah-death-threats--that-vaccine-how-it-all-went-wrong/|title=Bill Gates, Trevor Noah, death threats & that vaccine: how it all went wrong|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> following the publication of a now retracted story in [[News24]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-the-bill-and-melinda-gates-foundation-for-africa-vaccine-story-20200405|title=Apology to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation for 'Africa vaccine' story|date=2020-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[Trevor Noah]] stated that he received hate mail for conducting the interview on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' with Gates where it was falsely reported that Gates made the claim.<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\" /> \n\nFake news that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of COVID-19 symptoms also spread in the country during this period as it also did in other countries around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says '5G causing Covid-19 deaths' is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Africa|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/ National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Government COVID-19 website]\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 Government officials' speeches]\n*[https://datastudio.google.com/u/0/reporting/1b60bdc7-bec7-44c9-ba29-be0e043d8534/page/hrUIB Dashboard by Data Science for Social Impact Research Group, University of Pretoria]\n*[https://coronamap.co.za Corona virus map]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 World Health Organization (WHO) COVID-19 pandemic information]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jeandr\u00e9 du Toit", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "Casamance conflict", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict    = Casamance conflict\n|campaign    =\n|image       = Alerte aux mines terrestres \u00e0 Oussouye.jpg\n|caption     = {{nowrap|Painting in [[Oussouye]] warning of [[land mine]]s in the area.}}\n|date        = 1982 \u2013 1 May 2014 (main conflict)<br>2015 \u2013 present (low-level violence)\n|place       = [[Casamance]], [[Senegal]]\n|status      = Unilateral ceasefire;<ref name=\"Warsintheworld.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.warsintheworld.com/index.php/2014/05/01/senegal-movement-for-the-democratic-forces-of-casamance-mfdc-rebels-declare-unilateral-truce/|title=Senegal: Movement for the Democratic Forces of Casamance (MFDC) rebels declare unilateral truce \u00bb Wars in the World|publisher=Warsintheworld.com|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> ongoing low-level violence.\n|combatant1  = {{flag|Senegal}}<br/>{{flag|Guinea-Bissau}} <small>([[Jo\u00e3o Bernardo Vieira|Vieira government]], 1998\u201399)</small>{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|pp=400, 401}}<br/>'''Non-combat support''':<br>{{flag|Morocco}}<ref name=\"Wikileaks\">{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06DAKAR3016_a.html|title=ESCALATION IN REBEL ATTACKS|work=Wikileaks|date=27 December 2006|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n|combatant2  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Casamance (2012).svg}}{{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance|MFDC]]\n* Three main factions (Sadio, Badiatte, and Diatta Groups)<ref name=\"Boundaries\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jun/19/casamance-guinea-bissau-gambia-senegal |title=Boundaries of Casamance remain blurred after 30 years of conflict |author=Christophe Ch\u00e2telot |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=14 December 2017 }}</ref>\n* Various splinter factions{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|pp=400, 401}}\n{{flagdeco|Guinea-Bissau}} [[Guinea-Bissau Civil War|Guinea-Bissau rebels]] <small>(1998\u201399)</small>{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=400}}<br/>'''Alleged support''':<br>{{flag|Gambia}} (until 2017)<ref name=KOwq>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/07BANJUL250_a.html|title=FURTHER STRAINS IN TIES WITH SENEGAL OVER CASAMANCE|work=Wikileaks|date=15 May 2007|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n|commander1  = {{flagdeco|Senegal}} [[Abdou Diouf]] (1982\u20132000)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Senegal}} [[Abdoulaye Wade]] (2000\u20132012)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Senegal}} [[Macky Sall]] (2012\u20132014)\n|commander2  = {{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Augustin Diamacoune Senghor]] (1982\u20132007)<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/><br>\n{{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Salif Sadio]]{{WIA}} (2007\u20132014)<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/><br>\n{{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Caesar Badiatte]] (1982\u20132014)<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/><br>\n{{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Mamadou Niantang Diatta]] (1982\u20132014)<ref name=KOwq/><ref name=TorI/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09DAKAR1440_a.html|title=INCREASED VIOLENCE AND A POTENTIAL NEW LEADER|work=Wikileaks|date=25  November 2009|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n{{flagdeco|Guinea-Bissau}} [[Ansumane Man\u00e9]] <small>(1998\u201399)</small>{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=400}}\n|strength1   = {{flagdeco|Senegal}} [[Armed Forces of Senegal]]: Thousands (2012)<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/><br/>{{flagicon|Morocco}} 500 Moroccan bomb disposal advisors<ref name=TorI>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/07DAKAR275_a.html|title=DETERIORATION IN THE CASAMANCE|work=Wikileaks|date=2 February 2007|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n|strength2   = 180 (2006)<ref name=Yari/>\n|casualties1 = \n|casualties2 = \n|casualties3 = 5,000 killed in total since 1982<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinguinbali.com/index.php?lang=en&mod=news&task=view_news&cat=3&id=1392 |title=Casamance: no peace after thirty years of war - GuinGuinBali.com |publisher=Guinguinbali.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130103013015/http://www.guinguinbali.com/index.php?lang=en&mod=news&task=view_news&cat=3&id=1392 |archivedate=3 January 2013 }}</ref><br> 60,000 internally displaced <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/africarenewal/magazine/april-2005/peace-pact-raises-hope-senegal|title=Peace pact raises hope in Senegal|date=April 2005|author=Harsch, Ernest}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Casamance conflict''' is an ongoing low-level conflict that has been waged between the [[Politics of Senegal|Government of Senegal]] and the [[Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance]] (MFDC) since 1982. On May 1, 2014 the leader of the MFDC sued for peace and declared a unilateral ceasefire.\n\nThe MFDC has called for the independence of the [[Casamance]] region, whose population is religiously and ethnically distinct from the rest of Senegal.<ref name=JuT>{{cite web|url=http://ucdp.uu.se/#country/433|title=Database - Uppsala Conflict Data Program (UCDP)|publisher=Ucdp.uu.se}}{{verification needed|date=November 2016}}</ref> The bloodiest years of the conflict were during the 1992\u20132001 period and resulted in over a thousand battle related deaths.<ref name=JuT/>\n\nOn December 30, 2004 an agreement was reached between the MFDC and the government which promised to provide the voluntary integration of MFDC fighters into the country's paramilitary forces, economic recovery programmes for Casamance, de-mining and aid to returning refugees.<ref name=JuT/> Nevertheless, some hard-line factions of the MFDC soon defected from elements of the MFDC who had signed the agreement and no negotiations took place following the breakdown of talks in [[Foundiougne]] on 2 February 2005.<ref name=JuT/>\n\nFighting again emerged in 2010 and 2011 but waned following the April 2012 election of [[Macky Sall]]. Peace negotiations under the auspices of [[Community of Sant'Egidio|Saint Egidio community]] took place in [[Rome]] and on 14 December 2012, President Sall announced that Casamance would be a test-case for advanced decentralization policy.<ref name=JuT/>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Senegal Casamance.png|thumb|left|Map of the [[Casamance]] region (dark red) as part of wider [[Senegal]] ]]\nThe [[Casamance]] region is the southern region of Senegal which, although connected in the East to Senegal, is separated from the rest of Senegal by [[the Gambia]]. The principal inhabitants of the region are members of the [[Jola people|Jola]] ethnic group and many are [[Christians]] or [[animists]], unlike the majority of Senegalese who are [[Muslims]].<ref name=JuT/> The sentiment has existed amongst Diola that they do not benefit sufficiently from the region's richness and that Dakar, the capital, reaps most of the profit from the region's products.<ref name=JuT/>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n===1970s===\nIt was not before the 1970s that a genuine separatist sentiment emerged in Casamance. One of the recurring themes was that Northerners dominated the economy of the region.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Palgrave Macmillan| isbn = 978-3-319-90205-0| pages = 265\u2013292|editor= Lotje de Vries |editor2=Pierre Englebert |editor3=Mareike Schomerus | last = Foucher| first = Vincent| title = Secessionism in African politics aspiration, grievance, performance, disenchantment| chapter = The Mouvement des Forces D\u00e9mocratiques de Casamance: The Illusion of Separatism in Senegal?| location = Cham| date = 2019}}</ref>\n\n===1980s===\nIn the 1980s, resentment about the marginalization and exploitation of Casamance by the Senegalese central government gave rise to an independence movement in form of the MFDC, which was officially founded in 1982. This initial movement managed to unite Jola and other ethnic groups in the region, such as [[Fula people|Fulani]], [[Mandinka people|Mandinka]] and [[Bainuk people|Bainuk]], and led to rising popular resistance against the government and northerners. The MFDC began to organise demonstrations, and tensions eventually escalated in massive riots in December 1983. The Senegalese government answered by dividing the Casamance province into two smaller regions, probably in order to split and weaken the independence movement. This only heightened tensions, and the government began to jail MFDC leaders such as [[Augustin Diamacoune Senghor]].{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=399}}\n\nAnother factor in the growing independence movement was the failure of the [[Senegambia Confederation]] in 1989, which had economically benefited Casamance and whose end only worsened the situation of Casamance's population.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=399}}\n\n===1990s===\n[[File:Flag of Casamance.svg|thumb|left|The [[Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance|MFDC]] and other separatist groups originally used this horizontal white-green-red tricolor as [[Casamance]]'s national flag{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=396}} ]]\n\nThe discovery of oil in the region emboldened the MFDC to organise mass demonstrations for immediate independence in 1990, which were brutally suppressed by the Senegalese military. This pushed the MFDC into armed rebellion. The following fighting was vicious, and 30,000 civilians were displaced by 1994. Several [[ceasefire]]s were agreed during the 1990s, but none lasted, often also due to splits within the MFDC along ethnic lines and between those ready negotiate and those who refused to lay down their weapons. In 1992 the MFDC divided into two main groups, Front Sud and Front Nord. Whereas Front Sud was dominated by Jola and called for full independence, Front Nord included both Jola as well as non-Jola tribesmen and was ready to work with the government based on a failed agreement of 1991.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|pp=399, 400}} Another ceasefire in 1993 led to the break-off of hardline rebel groups from the MFDC. These continued to attack the military.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=400}}\n\nThe Senegalese military relocated thousands of soldiers from the northern provinces to Casamance in 1995 in an attempt to finally crush the uprising. The northern soldiers often mistreated the local population and did not differentiate between those who supported the rebels and government loyalists. By this time, the rebels had established bases in [[Guinea-Bissau]], reportedly being supplied with arms by Bissau-Guinean [[Military of Guinea-Bissau|military commander]] [[Ansumane Man\u00e9]]. Man\u00e9's alleged support for the separatists was one factor which led to the [[Guinea-Bissau Civil War]] that erupted in 1998. When Senegal decided to send its military into Guinea-Bissau to fight for the local government against Man\u00e9's forces, the latter and the MFDC formed a full alliance. The two rebel movements started to fight side by side in both Senegal as well as Guinea-Bissau.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=400}} Although the Senegal-supported government of Guinea-Bissau collapsed, the following MFDC-sympathetic regime was also overthrown in May 1999.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|pp=400, 401}}\n\nIn an renewed offensive against the separatists between April and June 1999, the Senegalese military shelled Casamance's ''de facto'' capital [[Ziguinchor]] for the first time, causing numerous civilian casualties and the displacement of 20,000 people along the Senegal\u2013Guinea-Bissau border. From then on, fighting mostly took place in the eastern [[Kolda Region]]. Another attempt at peace talks started in December 1999, with Senegalese and MFDC representatives meeting in [[Banjul]]. Both sides agreed to a ceasefire.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=401}}\n\n===2000s===\nPeace talks resumed in January 2000, with both sides attempting to end the military conflict and aiming at restoring political and economic normality to Casamance. Discussions were held about the MFDC transforming into a political party, but the talks were hindered by the MFDC's factionalism, and the refusal of the Senegalese government to even consider Casamance's independence. As result, the peace talks collapsed in November 2000, with MFDC leader Augustin Diamacoune Senghor declaring that his group would continue to fight until achieving independence. A new ceasefire was agreed to in March 2001, but failed to stop the conflict. Meanwhile, internal divisions deepened among the MFDC about the movement's aims and Senghor's leadership.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=401}}\n\nOn 30 December 2004, the two sides of the conflict signed a truce, which lasted until August 2006.<ref name=Yari>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06DAKAR2012_a.html|title=THE 2004 TRUCE HAS ENDED|work=Wikileaks|date=21 August 2006|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince the split, low-level fighting has continued in the region. Another round of negotiations took place in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4133881.stm|title=Senegal to sign Casamance accord|work=BBC|date=30 December 2004|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> Its results were, however, proved partial and armed clashes between MFDC factions and the army continued in 2006, prompting thousands of civilians to flee across the border to [[The Gambia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irinnews.org/news/2006/12/05/attacks-casamance-despite-peace-move|title=Attacks in Casamance despite peace move|work=Irin News|date=5 December 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 January 2006, anti-talk MFDC insurgents committed several armed robberies and killed a senior Diouloulou official.  The insurgents notoriously adopted [[Rick Derringer]]'s \"Rock 'n' Roll Hoochie Koo\" as an anthem of sorts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06DAKAR43_a.html|title=ARE HARDLINERS TRYING TO SABOTAGE THE PEACE PROCESS?|work=Wikileaks|date=6 January 2006|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2006, rebels attacked a Senegalese army outpost in Nyassia. The incident came after Guinea Bissauan troops shelled insurgent positions in Baraca Mandioca, Bazere, Koumere, Kassou and other areas, earlier in April.<ref name=MoT>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06DAKAR1005_a.html|title=CHIEF REBEL STRONGER THAN ANTICIPATED|work=Wikileaks|date=26 April 2006|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2006, a Senegalese army vehicle triggered a landmine in the outskirts of Sindian.<ref name=\"Wikileaks\" />\n\nOn 20 December 2006, rebels attacked a Senegalese army vehicle near the village of Kagnaru, killing 2 and wounding 14 soldiers.<ref name=\"Wikileaks\" />\n\nThe attacks came as a response to the demining process launched by  the Senegalese army without consultations with the rebels. The demining operation was led by [[Royal Moroccan Army|Moroccan army]] experts.<ref name=\"Wikileaks\" />\n\nOn 13 January 2007, [[Augustin Diamacoune Senghor]], the charismatic leader of MDFC died in [[Paris]]. His death hastened the split of the MDFC, which divided into three major armed factions, led by Salif Sadio, Caesar Badiatte, and Mamadou Niantang Diatta respectively.<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/>\n\nOn 31 July 2007, one rebel was killed and one injured, after opposing factions of MDFC engaged in a skirmish outside the Bai Pol village, Gambia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/07BANJUL449_a.html|title=\nCASAMANCE REBELS SKIRMISH IN THE GAMBIA|work=Wikileaks|date=22 August 2007|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 June 2009, MDFC gunmen killed 3 people in the area of Dailoulou.<ref name=TalK>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09DAKAR948_a.html|title=WAR AND BANDITRY IN THE CASAMANCE|work=Wikileaks|date=27 July 2009|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2009, radical MDFC militants killed a former  MFDC member, who at the time was serving as a peace process mediator.<ref name=TalK/>\n\nOn 25 August 2009, MFDC insurgents engaged in heavy clashes with security forces in the city of [[Ziguinchor]]; the [[University of Ziguinchor]] was among the buildings damaged during the firefight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/51/5104995_-africa-senegal-ct-heaviest-fighting-in-years-hits-casamance.html|title=Heaviest fighting in years hits Casamance|work=Wikileaks|date=26 August 2009|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2009, one soldier was killed after MFDC rebels fired at an army outpost in Diabir.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/51/5125079_-os-senegal-ct-soldier-killed-in-senegal-s-casamance.html|title=Soldier killed in Senegal's Casamance province |work=Wikileaks|date=4 September 2009|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2009, MFDC insurgents ambushed an army vehicle in the Kolda region. The insurgents attacked the troops in the vehicle with guns and [[rocket propelled grenades]] after they became stuck on a muddy road. Seven Senegalese troops, including a captain, were killed and a further four were wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09DAKAR1261_a.html|title=CASAMANCE REBELS KILL SEVEN SENEGALESE SOLDIERS|work=Wikileaks|date=6 October 2009|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n[[File:Flag of Casamance (2012).svg|thumb|right|By the 2010s, the [[Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance|MFDC]] had adopted a new flag for their rebellion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFKBN1EW0BF-OZATP |title=Gunmen kill 13 in Senegal's Casamance region - army |work=[[Reuters]] |date=7 January 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018 }}</ref> ]]\n\nBetween 16\u201321 March 2010, 3 soldiers were killed and 10 wounded, as Senegalese troops carried out operations in the  Baraf, Kassana and Mamatoro districts of Casamance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/31/319411_-os-senegal-mil-ct-senegalese-army-trying-to-sweep-out-rebel.html|title=Senegalese army trying to sweep out rebel MFDC bases in Casamance \n|work=Wikileaks|date=22 March 2010|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, an illegal shipment of arms from [[Iran]] was seized in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]]. The Senegalese government suspected that the arms were destined for the Casamance, and recalled its ambassador to [[Tehran]] over the matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-11998752|title=BBC News - Senegal recalls Tehran ambassador over arms shipment|work=BBC News|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> Heavy fighting occurred in December 2010 when about 100 MDFC fighters attempted to take Bignona south of the Gambian border supported by heavy weapons, such as mortars and machine guns. They were repulsed with several casualties by Senegalese soldiers who suffered seven dead in the engagement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.english.rfi.fr/africa/20101228-senegalese-army-sweeps-casamance-after-fight-separatists |title=Senegalese army sweeps Casamance after fight with separatists|publisher=RFI|date=28 December 2010 |accessdate=2011-04-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 August 2011, MFDC rebels robbed several people, on the Senoba-Ziguinchor road in northern Casamance, and later exchanged fire with soldiers outside the village of Diango.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/22/2291869_-africa-fwd-os-senegal-army-clashes-with-suspected-rebels-in.html|title=Army clashes with suspected rebels in Casamance|work=Wikileaks|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 December 2011, Senegal media reported that 12 soldiers were killed in Senegal's Casamance region following a separatist rebel attack on an army base near the town of Bignona.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/e0c16e804980f20b85999f63aa8ce1bf/12-Soldiers-killed-as-violence-in-Senegal-continues-20111221|title=12 Soldiers killed as violence in Senegal continues|publisher=Sabc.co.za|accessdate=12 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018165519/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/e0c16e804980f20b85999f63aa8ce1bf/12-Soldiers-killed-as-violence-in-Senegal-continues-20111221|archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nThree soldiers were killed during a clash 50 kilometers (31&nbsp;mi) north of [[Ziguinchor]]. The Senegalese government blamed the conflict on separatists in the region on February 14, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/02/2012214134754565909.html|agency=Al Jazeera|date=14 February 2012|title=Senegalese troops 'killed in attack'}}</ref>\n\nTwo attacks occurred on 11 and 23 March 2012, leaving 4 soldiers killed and 8 injured.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/385189/1/soldier-killed-four-wounded-in-senegal-rebel-attac.html|agency=Modern Ghana|date=23 March 2012|title=Soldier Killed, Four Wounded In Senegal Rebel Attack}}</ref>\n\nSince April 2012, peace in the Casamance has been a top priority for the administration of [[Senegalese President]] [[Macky Sall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hdcentre.org/activities/senegal/|agency=Centre for Humanitarian Dialogue|title=Activities - Senegal}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2013, four people were killed during a bank robbery perpetrated by the MFDC in the town of Kafoutine; the rebels stole a total of $8,400.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://africajournalismtheworld.com/2013/02/03/senegal-casamance-separatist-insurgency-kills-four/|title=Casamance separatist insurgency kills four|work=Reuters|date=3 February 2013|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2014, one of the leaders of the Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance, Salif Sadio, sued for peace and declared a unilateral cease-fire after secret talks held at the Vatican between his forces and the Government of Senegal led by Macky Sall.<ref name=\"Warsintheworld.com\"/>\n\n[[Yahya Jammeh]] has been known to recruit MFDC fighters into the Gambian military, reportedly since they are more inclined to be loyal to Jammeh's regime than the people of [[the Gambia]].<ref name=\"African Arguments 2016\">{{cite web | title=Gambia: Why the army may be the key to getting Jammeh to step down | website=African Arguments | date=2016-12-16 | url=http://africanarguments.org/2016/12/16/gambia-why-the-army-may-be-the-key-to-getting-jammeh-to-step-down/ | access-date=2018-02-17}}</ref> During the 2017 [[ECOWAS military intervention in the Gambia]], MFDC rebels supported pro-Jammeh forces.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201701180043.html|title=Gambia: Jammeh 'Imports Rebels'|first=C. Y.|last=Kwanue|date=18 January 2017|publisher=allAfrica|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nMember of the group were suspected of being behind an ambush that left 13 people dead near the town of [[Ziguinchor]] on 6 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20180106-senegal-gunmen-kill-least-13-southern-casamance-region |title=Gunmen killed at least 13 people Saturday in Senegal who were gathering firewood in the forest, the military said. |publisher=France24 |access-date=6 January 2018 |date=6 January 2018 }}</ref> Leaders of the MFDC, however, have denied responsibility for the execution-style killing, which they say was connected with the illegal harvesting of teak wood and rosewood from the forested region, not the gathering of firewood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pulse.ng/news/world/in-senegal-rebels-blame-casamance-massacre-on-logging-feud-id7816254.html |title=Rebels blame Casamance massacre on logging feud |publisher=Pulse News Agency International by AFP | access-date=27 January 2018 |date=9 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book\n|last=Minahan\n|first=James \n|title= Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations: Ethnic and National Groups Around the World\n|year=2002\n|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]\n|isbn=\n|url=\n|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite paper |year=2011 |title=Understanding The Casamance Conflict: A Background |series=KAIPTC Monograph No. 7 |last=Fall |first=A\u00efssatou |url=http://dspace.cigilibrary.org/jspui/handle/123456789/31669 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130414141324/http://dspace.cigilibrary.org/jspui/handle/123456789/31669 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-04-14 }}\n* Eric Morier-Genoud, \"Sant\u2019 Egidio et la paix. Interviews de Don Matteo Zuppi & Ricardo Cannelli\", _ [https://web.archive.org/web/20110723173757/http://www2.unil.ch/lefaitmissionnaire/pages/tables_publi/lfm13_tbl.html ''LFM. Sciences sociales et missions''] _, Oct 2003, pp.&nbsp;119\u2013145\n* Foucher, Vincent, \u2018The Mouvement Des Forces D\u00e9mocratiques de Casamance: The Illusion of Separatism in Senegal?\u2019, in Secessionism in African Politics Aspiration, Grievance, Performance, Disenchantment, ed. by Lotje de Vries, Pierre Englebert, and Mareike Schomerus (Cham: Palgrave Macmillan, 2019), pp.&nbsp;265\u201392\n\n{{Post-Cold War African conflicts}}\n\n[[Category:Casamance]]\n[[Category:20th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:21st-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:Civil wars involving the states and peoples of Africa]]\n[[Category:Civil wars post-1945]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2013]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2018]]\n[[Category:Separatism in Senegal]]\n[[Category:Separatist rebellion-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Senegal]]\n[[Category:Military of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Politics of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Political violence in Senegal]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Guinea-Bissau]]\n[[Category:The Gambia\u2013Senegal relations]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Gambia]]\n[[Category:Guinea-Bissau\u2013Senegal relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict    = Casamance conflict\n|campaign    =\n|image       = Alerte aux mines terrestres \u00e0 Oussouye.jpg\n|caption     = {{nowrap|Painting in [[Oussouye]] warning of [[land mine]]s in the area.}}\n|date        = 1982 \u2013 1 May 2014 (main conflict)<br>2015 \u2013 present (low-level violence)\n|place       = [[Casamance]], [[Senegal]]\n|status      = Unilateral ceasefire;<ref name=\"Warsintheworld.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.warsintheworld.com/index.php/2014/05/01/senegal-movement-for-the-democratic-forces-of-casamance-mfdc-rebels-declare-unilateral-truce/|title=Senegal: Movement for the Democratic Forces of Casamance (MFDC) rebels declare unilateral truce \u00bb Wars in the World|publisher=Warsintheworld.com|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> ongoing low-level violence.\n|combatant1  = {{flag|Senegal}}<br/>{{flag|Guinea-Bissau}} <small>([[Jo\u00e3o Bernardo Vieira|Vieira government]], 1998\u201399)</small>{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|pp=400, 401}}<br/>'''Non-combat support''':<br>{{flag|Morocco}}<ref name=\"Wikileaks\">{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06DAKAR3016_a.html|title=ESCALATION IN REBEL ATTACKS|work=Wikileaks|date=27 December 2006|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n|combatant2  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Casamance (2012).svg}}{{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance|MFDC]]\n* Three main factions (Sadio, Badiatte, and Diatta Groups)<ref name=\"Boundaries\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jun/19/casamance-guinea-bissau-gambia-senegal |title=Boundaries of Casamance remain blurred after 30 years of conflict |author=Christophe Ch\u00e2telot |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=19 June 2012 |accessdate=14 December 2017 }}</ref>\n* Various splinter factions{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|pp=400, 401}}\n{{flagdeco|Guinea-Bissau}} [[Guinea-Bissau Civil War|Guinea-Bissau rebels]] <small>(1998\u201399)</small>{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=400}}<br/>'''Alleged support''':<br>{{flag|Gambia}} (until 2017)<ref name=KOwq>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/07BANJUL250_a.html|title=FURTHER STRAINS IN TIES WITH SENEGAL OVER CASAMANCE|work=Wikileaks|date=15 May 2007|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n|commander1  = {{flagdeco|Senegal}} [[Abdou Diouf]] (1982\u20132000)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Senegal}} [[Abdoulaye Wade]] (2000\u20132012)<br>\n{{flagdeco|Senegal}} [[Macky Sall]] (2012\u20132014)\n|commander2  = {{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Augustin Diamacoune Senghor]] (1982\u20132007)<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/><br>\n{{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Salif Sadio]]{{WIA}} (2007\u20132014)<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/><br>\n{{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Caesar Badiatte]] (1982\u20132014)<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/><br>\n{{flagdeco|Casamance}} [[Mamadou Niantang Diatta]] (1982\u20132014)<ref name=KOwq/><ref name=TorI/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09DAKAR1440_a.html|title=INCREASED VIOLENCE AND A POTENTIAL NEW LEADER|work=Wikileaks|date=25  November 2009|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n{{flagdeco|Guinea-Bissau}} [[Ansumane Man\u00e9]] <small>(1998\u201399)</small>{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=400}}\n|strength1   = {{flagdeco|Senegal}} [[Armed Forces of Senegal]]: Thousands (2012)<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/><br/>{{flagicon|Morocco}} 500 Moroccan bomb disposal advisors<ref name=TorI>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/07DAKAR275_a.html|title=DETERIORATION IN THE CASAMANCE|work=Wikileaks|date=2 February 2007|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n|strength2   = 180 (2006)<ref name=Yari/>\n|casualties1 = \n|casualties2 = \n|casualties3 = 5,000 killed in total since 1982<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinguinbali.com/index.php?lang=en&mod=news&task=view_news&cat=3&id=1392 |title=Casamance: no peace after thirty years of war - GuinGuinBali.com |publisher=Guinguinbali.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130103013015/http://www.guinguinbali.com/index.php?lang=en&mod=news&task=view_news&cat=3&id=1392 |archivedate=3 January 2013 }}</ref><br> 60,000 internally displaced <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/africarenewal/magazine/april-2005/peace-pact-raises-hope-senegal|title=Peace pact raises hope in Senegal|date=April 2005|author=Harsch, Ernest}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Casamance conflict''' is an ongoing low-level conflict that has been waged between the [[Politics of Senegal|Government of Senegal]] and the [[Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance]] (MFDC) since 1982. On May 1, 2014 the leader of the MFDC sued for peace and declared a unilateral ceasefire.\n\nThe MFDC has called for the independence of the [[Casamance]] region, whose population is religiously and ethnically distinct from the rest of Senegal.<ref name=JuT>{{cite web|url=http://ucdp.uu.se/#country/433|title=Database - Uppsala Conflict Data Program (UCDP)|publisher=Ucdp.uu.se}}{{verification needed|date=November 2016}}</ref> The bloodiest years of the conflict were during the 1992\u20132001 period and resulted in over a thousand battle related deaths.<ref name=JuT/>\n\nOn December 30, 2004 an agreement was reached between the MFDC and the government which promised to provide the voluntary integration of MFDC fighters into the country's paramilitary forces, economic recovery programmes for Casamance, de-mining and aid to returning refugees.<ref name=JuT/> Nevertheless, some hard-line factions of the MFDC soon defected from elements of the MFDC who had signed the agreement and no negotiations took place following the breakdown of talks in [[Foundiougne]] on 2 February 2005.<ref name=JuT/>\n\nFighting again emerged in 2010 and 2011 but waned following the April 2012 election of [[Macky Sall]]. Peace negotiations under the auspices of [[Community of Sant'Egidio|Saint Egidio community]] took place in [[Rome]] and on 14 December 2012, President Sall announced that Casamance would be a test-case for advanced decentralization policy.<ref name=JuT/>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Senegal Casamance.png|thumb|left|Map of the [[Casamance]] region (dark red) as part of wider [[Senegal]] ]]\nThe [[Casamance]] region is the southern region of Senegal which, although connected in the East to Senegal, is separated from the rest of Senegal by [[the Gambia]]. The principal inhabitants of the region are members of the [[Jola people|Jola]] ethnic group and many are [[Christians]] or [[animists]], unlike the majority of Senegalese who are [[Muslims]].<ref name=JuT/> The sentiment has existed amongst Diola that they do not benefit sufficiently from the region's richness and that Dakar, the capital, reaps most of the profit from the region's products.<ref name=JuT/>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n===1970s===\nIt was not before the 1970s that a genuine separatist sentiment emerged in Casamance. One of the recurring themes was that Northerners dominated the economy of the region.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Palgrave Macmillan| isbn = 978-3-319-90205-0| pages = 265\u2013292| editors = Lotje de Vries, Pierre Englebert, Mareike Schomerus (eds.)| last = Foucher| first = Vincent| title = Secessionism in African politics aspiration, grievance, performance, disenchantment| chapter = The Mouvement des Forces D\u00e9mocratiques de Casamance: The Illusion of Separatism in Senegal?| location = Cham| date = 2019}}</ref>\n\n===1980s===\nIn the 1980s, resentment about the marginalization and exploitation of Casamance by the Senegalese central government gave rise to an independence movement in form of the MFDC, which was officially founded in 1982. This initial movement managed to unite Jola and other ethnic groups in the region, such as [[Fula people|Fulani]], [[Mandinka people|Mandinka]] and [[Bainuk people|Bainuk]], and led to rising popular resistance against the government and northerners. The MFDC began to organise demonstrations, and tensions eventually escalated in massive riots in December 1983. The Senegalese government answered by dividing the Casamance province into two smaller regions, probably in order to split and weaken the independence movement. This only heightened tensions, and the government began to jail MFDC leaders such as [[Augustin Diamacoune Senghor]].{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=399}}\n\nAnother factor in the growing independence movement was the failure of the [[Senegambia Confederation]] in 1989, which had economically benefited Casamance and whose end only worsened the situation of Casamance's population.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=399}}\n\n===1990s===\n[[File:Flag of Casamance.svg|thumb|left|The [[Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance|MFDC]] and other separatist groups originally used this horizontal white-green-red tricolor as [[Casamance]]'s national flag{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=396}} ]]\n\nThe discovery of oil in the region emboldened the MFDC to organise mass demonstrations for immediate independence in 1990, which were brutally suppressed by the Senegalese military. This pushed the MFDC into armed rebellion. The following fighting was vicious, and 30,000 civilians were displaced by 1994. Several [[ceasefire]]s were agreed during the 1990s, but none lasted, often also due to splits within the MFDC along ethnic lines and between those ready negotiate and those who refused to lay down their weapons. In 1992 the MFDC divided into two main groups, Front Sud and Front Nord. Whereas Front Sud was dominated by Jola and called for full independence, Front Nord included both Jola as well as non-Jola tribesmen and was ready to work with the government based on a failed agreement of 1991.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|pp=399, 400}} Another ceasefire in 1993 led to the break-off of hardline rebel groups from the MFDC. These continued to attack the military.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=400}}\n\nThe Senegalese military relocated thousands of soldiers from the northern provinces to Casamance in 1995 in an attempt to finally crush the uprising. The northern soldiers often mistreated the local population and did not differentiate between those who supported the rebels and government loyalists. By this time, the rebels had established bases in [[Guinea-Bissau]], reportedly being supplied with arms by Bissau-Guinean [[Military of Guinea-Bissau|military commander]] [[Ansumane Man\u00e9]]. Man\u00e9's alleged support for the separatists was one factor which led to the [[Guinea-Bissau Civil War]] that erupted in 1998. When Senegal decided to send its military into Guinea-Bissau to fight for the local government against Man\u00e9's forces, the latter and the MFDC formed a full alliance. The two rebel movements started to fight side by side in both Senegal as well as Guinea-Bissau.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=400}} Although the Senegal-supported government of Guinea-Bissau collapsed, the following MFDC-sympathetic regime was also overthrown in May 1999.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|pp=400, 401}}\n\nIn an renewed offensive against the separatists between April and June 1999, the Senegalese military shelled Casamance's ''de facto'' capital [[Ziguinchor]] for the first time, causing numerous civilian casualties and the displacement of 20,000 people along the Senegal\u2013Guinea-Bissau border. From then on, fighting mostly took place in the eastern [[Kolda Region]]. Another attempt at peace talks started in December 1999, with Senegalese and MFDC representatives meeting in [[Banjul]]. Both sides agreed to a ceasefire.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=401}}\n\n===2000s===\nPeace talks resumed in January 2000, with both sides attempting to end the military conflict and aiming at restoring political and economic normality to Casamance. Discussions were held about the MFDC transforming into a political party, but the talks were hindered by the MFDC's factionalism, and the refusal of the Senegalese government to even consider Casamance's independence. As result, the peace talks collapsed in November 2000, with MFDC leader Augustin Diamacoune Senghor declaring that his group would continue to fight until achieving independence. A new ceasefire was agreed to in March 2001, but failed to stop the conflict. Meanwhile, internal divisions deepened among the MFDC about the movement's aims and Senghor's leadership.{{sfnp|Minahan|2002|p=401}}\n\nOn 30 December 2004, the two sides of the conflict signed a truce, which lasted until August 2006.<ref name=Yari>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06DAKAR2012_a.html|title=THE 2004 TRUCE HAS ENDED|work=Wikileaks|date=21 August 2006|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince the split, low-level fighting has continued in the region. Another round of negotiations took place in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4133881.stm|title=Senegal to sign Casamance accord|work=BBC|date=30 December 2004|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> Its results were, however, proved partial and armed clashes between MFDC factions and the army continued in 2006, prompting thousands of civilians to flee across the border to [[The Gambia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irinnews.org/news/2006/12/05/attacks-casamance-despite-peace-move|title=Attacks in Casamance despite peace move|work=Irin News|date=5 December 2006}}</ref> \n\nOn 2 January 2006, anti-talk MFDC insurgents committed several armed robberies and killed a senior Diouloulou official.  The insurgents notoriously adopted [[Rick Derringer]]'s \"Rock 'n' Roll Hoochie Koo\" as an anthem of sorts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06DAKAR43_a.html|title=ARE HARDLINERS TRYING TO SABOTAGE THE PEACE PROCESS?|work=Wikileaks|date=6 January 2006|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2006, rebels attacked a Senegalese army outpost in Nyassia. The incident came after Guinea Bissauan troops shelled insurgent positions in Baraca Mandioca, Bazere, Koumere, Kassou and other areas, earlier in April.<ref name=MoT>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06DAKAR1005_a.html|title=CHIEF REBEL STRONGER THAN ANTICIPATED|work=Wikileaks|date=26 April 2006|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 December 2006, a Senegalese army vehicle triggered a landmine in the outskirts of Sindian.<ref name=\"Wikileaks\" />\n\nOn 20 December 2006, rebels attacked a Senegalese army vehicle near the village of Kagnaru, killing 2 and wounding 14 soldiers.<ref name=\"Wikileaks\" />\n\nThe attacks came as a response to the demining process launched by  the Senegalese army without consultations with the rebels. The demining operation was led by [[Royal Moroccan Army|Moroccan army]] experts.<ref name=\"Wikileaks\" />\n\nOn 13 January 2007, [[Augustin Diamacoune Senghor]], the charismatic leader of MDFC died in [[Paris]]. His death hastened the split of the MDFC, which divided into three major armed factions, led by Salif Sadio, Caesar Badiatte, and Mamadou Niantang Diatta respectively.<ref name=\"Boundaries\"/>\n\nOn 31 July 2007, one rebel was killed and one injured, after opposing factions of MDFC engaged in a skirmish outside the Bai Pol village, Gambia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/07BANJUL449_a.html|title=\nCASAMANCE REBELS SKIRMISH IN THE GAMBIA|work=Wikileaks|date=22 August 2007|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 June 2009, MDFC gunmen killed 3 people in the area of Dailoulou.<ref name=TalK>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09DAKAR948_a.html|title=WAR AND BANDITRY IN THE CASAMANCE|work=Wikileaks|date=27 July 2009|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2009, radical MDFC militants killed a former  MFDC member, who at the time was serving as a peace process mediator.<ref name=TalK/>\n\nOn 25 August 2009, MFDC insurgents engaged in heavy clashes with security forces in the city of [[Ziguinchor]]; the [[University of Ziguinchor]] was among the buildings damaged during the firefight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/51/5104995_-africa-senegal-ct-heaviest-fighting-in-years-hits-casamance.html|title=Heaviest fighting in years hits Casamance|work=Wikileaks|date=26 August 2009|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2009, one soldier was killed after MFDC rebels fired at an army outpost in Diabir.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/51/5125079_-os-senegal-ct-soldier-killed-in-senegal-s-casamance.html|title=Soldier killed in Senegal's Casamance province |work=Wikileaks|date=4 September 2009|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2009, MFDC insurgents ambushed an army vehicle in the Kolda region. The insurgents attacked the troops in the vehicle with guns and [[rocket propelled grenades]] after they became stuck on a muddy road. Seven Senegalese troops, including a captain, were killed and a further four were wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09DAKAR1261_a.html|title=CASAMANCE REBELS KILL SEVEN SENEGALESE SOLDIERS|work=Wikileaks|date=6 October 2009|accessdate=2 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n[[File:Flag of Casamance (2012).svg|thumb|right|By the 2010s, the [[Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance|MFDC]] had adopted a new flag for their rebellion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFKBN1EW0BF-OZATP |title=Gunmen kill 13 in Senegal's Casamance region - army |work=[[Reuters]] |date=7 January 2018 |accessdate=21 June 2018 }}</ref> ]]\n\nBetween 16\u201321 March 2010, 3 soldiers were killed and 10 wounded, as Senegalese troops carried out operations in the  Baraf, Kassana and Mamatoro districts of Casamance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/31/319411_-os-senegal-mil-ct-senegalese-army-trying-to-sweep-out-rebel.html|title=Senegalese army trying to sweep out rebel MFDC bases in Casamance \n|work=Wikileaks|date=22 March 2010|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, an illegal shipment of arms from [[Iran]] was seized in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]]. The Senegalese government suspected that the arms were destined for the Casamance, and recalled its ambassador to [[Tehran]] over the matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-11998752|title=BBC News - Senegal recalls Tehran ambassador over arms shipment|work=BBC News|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> Heavy fighting occurred in December 2010 when about 100 MDFC fighters attempted to take Bignona south of the Gambian border supported by heavy weapons, such as mortars and machine guns. They were repulsed with several casualties by Senegalese soldiers who suffered seven dead in the engagement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.english.rfi.fr/africa/20101228-senegalese-army-sweeps-casamance-after-fight-separatists |title=Senegalese army sweeps Casamance after fight with separatists|publisher=RFI|date=28 December 2010 |accessdate=2011-04-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 August 2011, MFDC rebels robbed several people, on the Senoba-Ziguinchor road in northern Casamance, and later exchanged fire with soldiers outside the village of Diango.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/gifiles/docs/22/2291869_-africa-fwd-os-senegal-army-clashes-with-suspected-rebels-in.html|title=Army clashes with suspected rebels in Casamance|work=Wikileaks|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 December 2011, Senegal media reported that 12 soldiers were killed in Senegal's Casamance region following a separatist rebel attack on an army base near the town of Bignona.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/e0c16e804980f20b85999f63aa8ce1bf/12-Soldiers-killed-as-violence-in-Senegal-continues-20111221|title=12 Soldiers killed as violence in Senegal continues|publisher=Sabc.co.za|accessdate=12 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018165519/http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/e0c16e804980f20b85999f63aa8ce1bf/12-Soldiers-killed-as-violence-in-Senegal-continues-20111221|archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nThree soldiers were killed during a clash 50 kilometers (31 mi) north of [[Ziguinchor]]. The Senegalese government blamed the conflict on separatists in the region on February 14, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/02/2012214134754565909.html|agency=Al Jazeera|date=14 February 2012|title=Senegalese troops 'killed in attack'}}</ref>\n\nTwo attacks occurred on 11 and 23 March 2012, leaving 4 soldiers killed and 8 injured.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/385189/1/soldier-killed-four-wounded-in-senegal-rebel-attac.html|agency=Modern Ghana|date=23 March 2012|title=Soldier Killed, Four Wounded In Senegal Rebel Attack}}</ref>\n\nSince April 2012, peace in the Casamance has been a top priority for the administration of [[Senegalese President]] [[Macky Sall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hdcentre.org/activities/senegal/|agency=Centre for Humanitarian Dialogue|title=Activities - Senegal}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2013, four people were killed during a bank robbery perpetrated by the MFDC in the town of Kafoutine; the rebels stole a total of $8,400.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://africajournalismtheworld.com/2013/02/03/senegal-casamance-separatist-insurgency-kills-four/|title=Casamance separatist insurgency kills four|work=Reuters|date=3 February 2013|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2014, one of the leaders of the Movement of Democratic Forces of Casamance, Salif Sadio, sued for peace and declared a unilateral cease-fire after secret talks held at the Vatican between his forces and the Government of Senegal led by Macky Sall.<ref name=\"Warsintheworld.com\"/>\n\n[[Yahya Jammeh]] has been known to recruit MFDC fighters into the Gambian military, reportedly since they are more inclined to be loyal to Jammeh's regime than the people of [[the Gambia]].<ref name=\"African Arguments 2016\">{{cite web | title=Gambia: Why the army may be the key to getting Jammeh to step down | website=African Arguments | date=2016-12-16 | url=http://africanarguments.org/2016/12/16/gambia-why-the-army-may-be-the-key-to-getting-jammeh-to-step-down/ | access-date=2018-02-17}}</ref> During the 2017 [[ECOWAS military intervention in the Gambia]], MFDC rebels supported pro-Jammeh forces.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201701180043.html|title=Gambia: Jammeh 'Imports Rebels'|first=C. Y.|last=Kwanue|date=18 January 2017|publisher=allAfrica|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref> \n\nMember of the group were suspected of being behind an ambush that left 13 people dead near the town of [[Ziguinchor]] on 6 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20180106-senegal-gunmen-kill-least-13-southern-casamance-region |title=Gunmen killed at least 13 people Saturday in Senegal who were gathering firewood in the forest, the military said. |publisher=France24 |access-date=6 January 2018 |date=6 January 2018 }}</ref> Leaders of the MFDC, however, have denied responsibility for the execution-style killing, which they say was connected with the illegal harvesting of teak wood and rosewood from the forested region, not the gathering of firewood. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pulse.ng/news/world/in-senegal-rebels-blame-casamance-massacre-on-logging-feud-id7816254.html |title=Rebels blame Casamance massacre on logging feud |publisher=Pulse News Agency International by AFP | access-date=27 January 2018 |date=9 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book\n|last=Minahan\n|first=James \n|title= Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations: Ethnic and National Groups Around the World\n|year=2002\n|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]\n|isbn=\n|url=\n|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite paper |year=2011 |title=Understanding The Casamance Conflict: A Background |series=KAIPTC Monograph No. 7 |last=Fall |first=A\u00efssatou |url=http://dspace.cigilibrary.org/jspui/handle/123456789/31669 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130414141324/http://dspace.cigilibrary.org/jspui/handle/123456789/31669 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-04-14 }}\n* Eric Morier-Genoud, \"Sant\u2019 Egidio et la paix. Interviews de Don Matteo Zuppi & Ricardo Cannelli\", _ [https://web.archive.org/web/20110723173757/http://www2.unil.ch/lefaitmissionnaire/pages/tables_publi/lfm13_tbl.html ''LFM. Sciences sociales et missions''] _, Oct 2003, pp.&nbsp;119\u2013145\n* Foucher, Vincent, \u2018The Mouvement Des Forces D\u00e9mocratiques de Casamance: The Illusion of Separatism in Senegal?\u2019, in Secessionism in African Politics Aspiration, Grievance, Performance, Disenchantment, ed. by Lotje de Vries, Pierre Englebert, and Mareike Schomerus (Cham: Palgrave Macmillan, 2019), pp. 265\u201392\n\n{{Post-Cold War African conflicts}}\n[[Category:Casamance]]\n[[Category:20th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:21st-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:Civil wars involving the states and peoples of Africa]]\n[[Category:Civil wars post-1945]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2013]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2018]]\n[[Category:Separatism in Senegal]]\n[[Category:Separatist rebellion-based civil wars]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Senegal]]\n[[Category:Military of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Politics of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Political violence in Senegal]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Guinea-Bissau]]\n[[Category:The Gambia\u2013Senegal relations]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Gambia]]\n[[Category:Guinea-Bissau\u2013Senegal relations]]\n", "name_user": "IznoRepeat", "label": "safe", "comment": "replace soft-deprecated editors parameter, gen fixes, misc cite cleaning", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casamance_conflict"}
